\begin{problem}{3.3.2 (15)}

Let $n$ be any natural. Define $I_n$ to be the set of all naturals $a$ such that $a < n$
and $a$ and $n$ are relatively prime. The \textbf{Euler totient function}  $\phi(n)$ is the size of $I_n$.

(a) Describe the sets I11 and I12.

(b) Explain why $\phi(n)=n-1$ if and only if is prime.

(c) Explain why if n is a power of 2, other than $2^0 = 1$, then $\phi(n) = n/2$.

(d) Explain why a natural $a < n$ has an inverse modulo n if and only if it is in In.

(e) Show that if a and b are in In, then a·b is congruent modulo n to a member of In.

(f) Give an example where a and b are in In but a + b is not congruent modulo n to any
member of In.
\end{problem}
\begin{sol}
Write your solution here.
\end{sol}



